{{Inorganic-compound-stub}}

[[File:Butterfly-joint.JPG|thumb|Butterfly joint]] A '''Dovetail key''', '''Dutchman Joint''', or '''Butterfly joint''' is a type of [[Woodworking joints|joint]] used either to hold two or more wooden boards together or to keep two halves of a board that have already started to split from splitting further. They may also be used to stabilize the core of a knothole, preventing it from dropping out over time. They are also commonly used as decorative inlays for non structural aesthetic purposes.<ref>https://www.canadianwoodworking.com/tipstechniques/butterfly-key</ref>
A Dovetail Key resembles two [[Dovetail joint|dovetails]] connected at the narrow part. A negative of the hole is cut out of the board the butterfly will be placed in and the butterfly is then fitted, keeping the joint together. The wood used for the butterfly is usually a contrasting wood, often walnut.
== History == Dovetail keys or Butterfly joints have been used both in decorative and structural joints since ancient times. They were prominently used in construction of the Cairo Dahshur Boats, a type of [[Khufu ship]] from the Egyptian middle kingdom.<ref>[[Pearce Paul Creasman]]. "The Cairo Dahshur Boats." TAMU, 2005. http://repository.tamu.edu/bitstream/handle/1969.1/4852/etd-tamu-2005C-ANTH-Creasman.pdf?sequence=10</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Creasman |first=Pearce Paul |year= |title=Dovetails or Lashings: A Case Study in Middle Kingdom Ship Construction (The Cairo Dahshur Boats) |journal=The 58th Annual Meeting of the American Research Center in Egypt |page=4 |publisher= |doi= |pmid= |pmc= |date=April 18, 2007 |url=http://citation.allacademic.com/meta/p_mla_apa_research_citation/1/8/1/6/6/pages181664/p181664-4.php |accessdate=25 December 2012}}</ref> They were also historically used in repairing cracks in Dutch tabletops in the 18th century. This is where the term Dutchman joint originates. The dovetail key was installed across the crack to stabilize and inhibit further movement of the crack.
== Modern use == Contemporary decorative dovetail keys are commonly seen in and associated with the work of [[George Nakashima]].<ref>Hargreaves, Andrea. "George Nakashima." Woodworkers Institute, 2008. http://www.woodworkersinstitute.com/page.asp?p=624</ref>
