{{Infobox book | name = Killer Company | image = Killer Company - James Hardie Exposed (book cover).jpg | caption = First edition cover | author = Matt Peacock | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = Australia | language = English | series = | subject = [[James Hardie Industries]] use of [[asbestos]] | genre = Non-fiction | publisher = [[ABC Commercial|ABC Books]] | pub_date = 2009 | english_pub_date = | media_type = Print, e-book | pages = | isbn = 978-0733325809 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Killer Company: James Hardie Exposed''''' is a 2009 Australian book by journalist [[Matt Peacock (journalist)|Matt Peacock]].
==Overview== The book documents how the use of harmful [[asbestos]] fibre in building materials produced by [[James Hardie Industries]] "led to the deaths of thousands of workers and customers, who were never informed of the dangers".<ref name=walk/> Working with asbestos products, such as "[[fibro]]", resulted in medical abnormalities, such as [[asbestosis]]. The book opens with the story of [[Bernie Banton]], former James Hardie employee, who suffered from asbestos-induced [[fibrosis]] and later died.<ref name=walk>Angela Welsh. [http://www.walkleys.com/books/490/ Review: Killer Company] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221234530/http://www.walkleys.com/books/490/ |date=2011-02-21 }} ''The Walkley Foundation'', 27 October 2009.</ref>
According to Peacock, James Hardie Industries circumvented the rules and regulations designed to protect the community from serious health hazards.<ref name=walk/> Peacock states that "Hardie embarked on a cold, calculated strategy to maximise profits, minimise compensation and conceal the culprits".<ref>Matt Peacock. [http://evatt.labor.net.au/publications/papers/227.html Australia's silent killer: James Hardie] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110218081304/http://evatt.labor.net.au/publications/papers/227.html |date=2011-02-18 }} ''[[Evatt Foundation]]''.</ref>
==Awards and Legacy== ''Killer Company'' was a finalist for the [[Walkley Award|Walkley]] non-fiction book of the year in 2009.<ref name=walk/> ''[[Devil's Dust]]'', a docudrama based on ''Killer Company'', was released in 2012, with [[Ewen Leslie]] portraying Peacock.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/devil-is-in-the-detail-20121107-28x5k.html|title=Devil is in the detail|author=Tim Elliott|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|date=8 November 2012|accessdate=14 March 2016}}</ref>
